<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1299,2010]" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,212,1300,1326]" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[227,365,1299,1326]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–30" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1974,1999]" captionTargetBox="[244,1347,349,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[237,1351,345,1949]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 23–30. Heterachthes hildebranti. 23–26), Male: 23) Dorsal habitus; 24) Ventral habitus; 25) Lateral habitus; 26) Head, frontal view. 27–30) Female: 27) Dorsal habitus; 28) Ventral habitus; 29) Lateral habitus; 30) Head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3693535" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3693535/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">Figs. 23–26</figureCitation>
). The second known male differs from the 
<typeStatus box="[816,908,1299,1325]" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">holotype</typeStatus>
by the first yellowish macula of the elytra slightly slender and not narrowed from anterior to posterior area, second yellowish macula of the elytra more narrowed toward suture, and not ending near it, prothorax slightly rounded laterally, and pronotum with punctures sparser.As no other reliable differences are found, we think that these differences are only variations in the species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1299,2010]" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,448,1443,1470]" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">Female. Description.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[465,606,1443,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–30" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1974,1999]" captionTargetBox="[244,1347,349,1946]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[237,1351,345,1949]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 23–30. Heterachthes hildebranti. 23–26), Male: 23) Dorsal habitus; 24) Ventral habitus; 25) Lateral habitus; 26) Head, frontal view. 27–30) Female: 27) Dorsal habitus; 28) Ventral habitus; 29) Lateral habitus; 30) Head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3693535" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3693535/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">Figs. 27–30</figureCitation>
). Yellowish band on anterior third of elytra subtriangular; circum-scutellar region, basal half of the elytra along suture and sides brown; ventral surface of thorax and legs slightly dark reddish brown. Antennae 1.7 times elytral length, reaching elytral apex at basal third of antennomere X; antennomeres III–V slenderer than in male.Antennal formula (ratio) based on length of antennomere III: scape = 0.57; pedicel = 0.12; IV = 0.56; V = 0.72; VI = 0.76; VII = 0.75; VIII = 0.72; IX = 0.67; X = 0.59; XI = 0.67. Apex of abdominal ventrite V rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1299,2010]" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1623,1650]" pageId="8" pageNumber="185">Dimensions,</emphasis>
male/female. Total length, 17.20/19.30; prothorax: length, 3.25/3.65; anterior width, 2.15/2.50; posterior width, 2.30/2.70; maximum prothoracic width, 2.35/3.05; humeral width, 3.50/4.00; elytral length, 10.65/12.10.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
